    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-23T09:49:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-23T09:49:00-05:00" n="882"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d882">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Lot 55D128: Black Book, Tab 141: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief, Far East</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ridgway</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Joint Chiefs of
                            Staff</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret   priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-23T23:49:00+09:00">23
                            December 1951—11:49 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>C–59977. For info, <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss> Adv HNC–625.</p>
                <p>“Report of Sub-Committee meeting on Item Nbr 4, convened 1100. <gloss
                        target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> devoted the entire morning to getting
                    Communists on the record with a definite answer to <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                        >UNC</gloss> proposal to exchange now the seriously sick and injured in
                    accordance with Articles 109 and 110 Geneva Convention. This was not
                    accomplished. All that could be established was that they would not agree now to
                    our request. In long and evasive responses to <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                        >UNC</gloss> questions on this subj Communists raised following points:</p>
                <list>
                    <item>“1. Communist Five Point proposal provides for early exchange of sick and
                        wounded. Aim of the <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> in raising this
                        question now is to delay rather than expedite the exchange of <gloss
                            target="#t_POW1">POW</gloss>s. </item>
                    <pb facs="1445" n="1429" xml:id="pg_1429"/>
                    <item>“2. <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> seeks to retain <gloss
                            target="#t_POW1">POW</gloss>s after cessation of hostilities.</item>
                    <item>“3. Where are the 44,259 missing persons? <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss> admitted yesterday it has detained 37,000.</item>
                    <item>“4. <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss>s statement that we do not know
                        when the armistice negotations will be concluded is an expression of its
                        policy toward the armistice.</item>
                    <item>“5. Does <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> agree to release all <gloss
                            target="#t_POW1">POW</gloss>s held by both sides after signing of
                        armistice agreement?</item>
                    <item>“6. <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> says 16,000 persons in its <gloss
                            target="#t_POW1">POW</gloss> camps which it will not release. This is
                        untenable.</item>
                    <item>“7. Regarding sick and wounded, <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> said
                        yesterday that some might decline to return. What does that mean? (<gloss
                            target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> invited attention to Para 3, Article 109
                        Geneva Convention).</item>
                    <item>“8. <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> is afraid to discuss principles
                        because that would disclose its objectives to the world.</item>
                </list>
                <p>“<gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> refuted all the above points.</p>
                <p>“A list of <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> held <gloss target="#t_POW1"
                        >POW</gloss>s was handed the Communists in which Korean names were written
                    in Korean characters and Chinese in Chinese characters. Recessed 1315 to
                    reconvene at 1500.”</p>
            </div>
